Intuition
Approach
First, I sort the candidates array so that duplicate elements come together. This helps in avoiding duplicate combinations and also allows pruning when the current sum exceeds the target.

I use backtracking to generate all possible combinations.

At every recursive call, I use a for loop to decide which element to pick next from the remaining candidates.

After choosing an element, I move to j + 1 because each candidate can be used only once.

To avoid duplicate combinations:

If the current element is the same as the previous element and both are at the same recursion level, I skip it.
This prevents generating the same combination multiple times while still allowing duplicate values to be used when needed (for example, [1,1,6]).
Since the array is sorted, if adding the current candidate makes the sum exceed the target, I stop exploring further because all following elements will also be larger.

Time Complexity
In the worst case, we explore all possible combinations, which is O(2^n).
Copying each valid combination into the result takes O(k), where k is the length of the combination.
Overall:

O(n * 2^n)
Space Complexity
The recursion depth can go up to n.
The temporary list diary can store up to n elements.
Auxiliary space:

O(n)
The output space is not included.

Code
class Solution:
    def combinationSum2(self, candidates: List[int], target: int) -> List[List[int]]:
        candidates.sort()
        result , diary , n = [] , [] , len(candidates)
        def fun(i,total):
            if total == target:
                result.append(diary.copy())
                return
            for j in range(i,n):
                if j > i and candidates[j] == candidates[j-1]:
                    continue
                if total + candidates[j] > target:
                    break
                diary.append(candidates[j])
                fun(j+1,total+candidates[j])
                diary.pop()
            return
        fun(0,0)
        return result
